Solution Let&rsquo;s define $f(u,v)$ be the maximum weight of an edge on the simple path between $u$ and $v$. We can sort all the edges in ascending order of weight, so the new edge we added always has the maximum weight in the current graph. Assume the weight of the current edge is $w$ and the size of the components it connects are $sz_x$ ans $sz_y$, so after adding this edge there will be $sz_x\cdot sz_y$ new pairs $(u,v)$ such that $f(u,v)=w$. We can use union find to merge components and track the size of each components.
Solution #include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt; #define forn(i, n) for (int i = 0; i &lt; int(n); ++i) #define for1(i, n) for (int i = 1; i &lt;= int(n); ++i) #define ms(a, x) memset(a, x, sizeof(a)) #define F first #define S second #define all(x) (x).begin(),(x).end()  using namespace std; typedef long long ll; typedef pair&lt;int, int&gt; pii; const int INF = 0x3f3f3f3f; mt19937 gen(chrono::steady_clock::now().time_since_epoch().count()); template&lt;typename... Args&gt; void rd(Args&amp;... args) {((cin &gt;&gt; args), ...);} template&lt;typename... Args&gt; void write(Args... args) { ((cout &lt;&lt; args &lt;&lt; &#34; &#34;), ...); cout&lt;&lt;endl;} constexpr int N=2e5+5; vector&lt;int&gt; fa,sz; int find(int x){ return fa[x]==x?x:fa[x]=find(fa[x]); } int main() { ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr); int n,m; cin&gt;&gt;n&gt;&gt;m; fa=sz=vector&lt;int&gt;(n+1); iota(all(fa),0); fill(all(sz),1); vector&lt;tuple&lt;int,int,int&gt;&gt; edge(n-1); array&lt;ll,N&gt; cnt{}; for(auto&amp; [c,u,v]:edge){ cin&gt;&gt;u&gt;&gt;v&gt;&gt;c; } sort(all(edge)); for(auto [c,x,y]:edge){ x=find(x),y=find(y); cnt[c]+=(ll)sz[x]*sz[y]; if(sz[x]&gt;sz[y]) swap(x,y); fa[x]=y; sz[y]+=sz[x]; } forn(i,2e5) cnt[i+1]+=cnt[i]; while(m--){ int x; cin&gt;&gt;x; cout&lt;&lt;cnt[x]&lt;&lt;&#39; &#39;; } return 0; }

为啥我就想不起来多源bfs呢？
Solution Let&rsquo;s call a cell bad if no adjacent cell has the same color, otherwise that cell is good.
If a good cell and a bad cell are adjacent, according to the definition, the good cell will change color in the next iteration while the bad cell not. As the result, the bad cell will turn into a good cell. Therefore, a bad cell won&rsquo;t change if all the cells are bad cells, otherwise it will become good when the nearest good cell reaches it. The left thing is to find the nearest good cell for all cells. This can be done using multi-source bfs.
Code {% raw %}
#include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt; #define forn(i, n) for (int i = 0; i &lt; int(n); ++i) #define for1(i, n) for (int i = 1; i &lt;= int(n); ++i) #define ms(a, x) memset(a, x, sizeof(a)) #define F first #define S second #define all(x) (x).begin(),(x).end() #define pb push_back  using namespace std; typedef long long ll; typedef pair&lt;int, int&gt; pii; const int INF = 0x3f3f3f3f; mt19937 gen(chrono::steady_clock::now().time_since_epoch().count()); template&lt;typename... T&gt; void rd(T&amp;... args) {((cin&gt;&gt;args), ...);} template&lt;typename... T&gt; void wr(T... args) {((cout&lt;&lt;args&lt;&lt;&#34; &#34;), ...);cout&lt;&lt;endl;} const vector&lt;pii&gt; dir{{1,0,},{-1,0},{0,1},{0,-1}}; int main() { ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr); int n,m,t; cin&gt;&gt;n&gt;&gt;m&gt;&gt;t; vector&lt;string&gt; G(n); for(auto&amp; it:G) cin&gt;&gt;it; queue&lt;pii&gt; q; auto cango=[&amp;](int x,int y){ return x&gt;=0&amp;&amp;x&lt;n&amp;&amp;y&gt;=0&amp;&amp;y&lt;m; }; vector&lt;vector&lt;int&gt;&gt; dis(n,vector&lt;int&gt;(m,-1)); forn(i,n){ forn(j,m){ bool ok=0; for(auto [dx,dy]:dir){ int x=i+dx,y=j+dy; if(cango(x,y)&amp;&amp;G[x][y]==G[i][j]) ok=1; } if(ok){ dis[i][j]=0; q.emplace(i,j); } } } while(!q.empty()){ auto [i,j]=q.front(); q.pop(); for(auto [dx,dy]:dir){ int x=i+dx,y=j+dy; if(cango(x,y)&amp;&amp;dis[x][y]==-1){ dis[x][y]=dis[i][j]+1; q.emplace(x,y); } } } while(t--){ int i,j; ll p; cin&gt;&gt;i&gt;&gt;j&gt;&gt;p; i--,j--; if(dis[i][j]==-1) cout&lt;&lt;G[i][j]&lt;&lt;endl; else if(dis[i][j]&gt;=p) cout&lt;&lt;((G[i][j]-&#39;0&#39;))&lt;&lt;endl; else cout&lt;&lt;((G[i][j]-&#39;0&#39;)^((p-dis[i][j])&amp;1))&lt;&lt;endl; } return 0; } {% endraw %}

很有意思的贪心
Solution First, let&rsquo;s force Vasya to change tire on everyday with negative temperature (even on consecutive days) so she will change tire for $2\cdot cnt$ time where $cnt$ is the number of days with negative temperature. If $cnt&gt;k$ obviously the answer is -1, otherwise the winter tire can still last for some extra days. Now let&rsquo;s see if we can use the winter tire on days with non-negative temperature. We can sort all the length of the consecutive days with non-negative temperature, so we can greedily use winter tires on those segments. For each segment we use, we save tire change twice. Finally let&rsquo;s see if we can use the winter tire until the last day after the last negative-temperature day.
Code #include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt; #define forn(i, n) for (int i = 0; i &lt; int(n); ++i) #define for1(i, n) for (int i = 1; i &lt;= int(n); ++i) #define ms(a, x) memset(a, x, sizeof(a)) #define F first #define S second #define all(x) (x).begin(),(x).end()  using namespace std; typedef long long ll; typedef pair&lt;int, int&gt; pii; const int INF = 0x3f3f3f3f; mt19937 gen(chrono::steady_clock::now().time_since_epoch().count()); template&lt;typename... Args&gt; void rd(Args&amp;... args) {((cin &gt;&gt; args), ...);} template&lt;typename... Ar&gt; void wr(Ar... ar) {((cout&lt;&lt;ar&lt;&lt;&#34; &#34;),...);cout&lt;&lt;endl;} int main() { ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr); int n,k; cin&gt;&gt;n&gt;&gt;k; vector&lt;int&gt; a(n),neg; forn(i,n){ cin&gt;&gt;a[i]; if(a[i]&lt;0) neg.push_back(i); } if(neg.empty()) return cout&lt;&lt;0,0; if(neg.size()&gt;k) return cout&lt;&lt;-1,0; vector&lt;int&gt; xs; for(int i=1;i&lt;(int)size(neg);i++) xs.push_back(neg[i]-neg[i-1]-1); sort(all(xs)); int ans=int(size(neg))*2; k-=size(neg); for(auto i:xs){ if(k&gt;=i){ k-=i; ans-=2; }else break; } if(n-neg.back()-1&lt;=k) ans--; cout&lt;&lt;ans; return 0; }

Solution First let&rsquo;s consider the case where $\max(h_{i + 1}, \ldots, h_{j - 1}) &lt; \min(h_i, h_j)$. $h_i$ could be lower or higher than $h_j$. There can be multiple $i$ that satisfies the condition and we can observe the leftmost $i$ is the first that $h_i\ge h_j$, let&rsquo;s denote this $i_{min}$, other $i$ between $[i_{min},j]$ must satisfy that $h_i$ is the maximum value among $[i,j-1]$. This can be solved using monotonic stack. Assume we store the indices in the stack, when adding a new index $j$, all the indices that will be removed are a valid position to jump to $j$, so we can do dp and update the minimum number of moves. The time complexity is $O(n)$.
The second case is similar.
Code #include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt; using namespace std; int main() { ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr); int n; cin&gt;&gt;n; vector&lt;int&gt; a(n); for(auto&amp; it:a) cin&gt;&gt;it; vector&lt;int&gt; dp(n,n); dp[0]=0; vector&lt;int&gt; h{0},l{0}; for(int i=1;i&lt;n;i++){ dp[i]=min(dp[i],dp[i-1]+1); while(!h.empty()&amp;&amp;a[i]&gt;=a[h.back()]){ int x=a[h.back()]; h.pop_back(); if(a[i]&gt;x&amp;&amp;!h.empty()) dp[i]=min(dp[i],dp[h.back()]+1); } while(!l.empty()&amp;&amp;a[i]&lt;=a[l.back()]){ int x=a[l.back()]; l.pop_back(); if(a[i]&lt;x&amp;&amp;!l.empty()) dp[i]=min(dp[i],dp[l.back()]+1); } h.push_back(i); l.push_back(i); } cout&lt;&lt;dp[n-1]; return 0; }

